  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">This unsigned, draft of a poem was presumably written by Maria Weston Chapman. It is entitled, &quot;June, the King of Countr[y]man.&quot; The poem begins: &quot;There once was a man much as ever you all; When the British came over he flurried and frowned; ...&quot; On page two, following the poem, is the note: &quot;A very rough copy.&quot;</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">This poem was written on a torn copy of a circular letter by Maria Weston Chapman to Dear Friend, dated Boston, 1840. For a complete copy of the circular letter, see Call No. Ms.A.9.2 v.14, p.98 .</subfield>
  </datafield>
